Hey Zeshan,

I had a look at your recommendations.
Thanks a lot for taking the time to give your input.
Please continue doing so. I have a LOT to learn when it comes to async work, etc. (and others :-D)
I fully understand what you suggest.
Here are my thoughts though, but please let me know what you think.

- OrganisationTests.cs (Line 36) 
	- On your question: ==Needs a GetAwaiter().GetResult()==
	- AdjustOrganistationDaylightSavingSettings will mostly be used by a service, which will never need to give any feedback
	- I wanted to test how it would work if I call it as such, so I dont want to wait for a result
	- I wanted to kick off the method and then check the logs to see if it goes through all the steps
	- It ended up working this way, therefore I didnt want to add the GetAwaiter and GetResult
	- I did, however, want to still allow future usage of this method to be able to Await a Result, but I don't want to now
	- Please let me know what you think?
	- I am learning a LOT about async during this techdebt story :-)
- OrganisationRepository.cs (Line 35)
	- From this question: ==do we need to retry this in case of failures?==
	- I'm actually not sure if we need to retry this.
	- It is the same as what I said above. I just want to kick it off and not worry.
	- It will be used as a service, so it will run maybe once a day, so if the call is missed, the next day it will be done.
	- What I have seen with some retries are that it retries very quickly, in this case it will try to set a lot of organisations settings
	- Ultimately I want to just say DO IT, then not worry or get feedback. I will kick it off again the next day
	- I was even thinking of using: httpNoRetriesButWithElasticStrategy :-)
	- What do you think?
- Program.cs (Line 607)
	- On your suggestion: ==Needs GetAwaiter().GetResult() or method can be made async and used with await==
	- Same reason as for the first point that I never used the Getwaiter or GetResult
	- I don't currenlty want to wait for the result, as I just want to kick it off
	- And this is a test app, so I wanted to use it to test the above
	- I could also confirm in swagger that this works well
	- What do you think?
- NOW my question :-) 
	- Zonika mentioned I need to rather put all this logic in the Internal Client
	- From what I can see it happens here: MiX.ConfigInternal.Api.Client
